Definition: or (shortened) דֹּד; from an unused root meaning properly, to boil, i.e.; (figuratively) to love; by implication, a love-token, lover, friend; specifically an uncle; (well-) beloved, father's brother, love, uncle.
from the same as {{h1730}}; a pot (for boiling); also (by resemblance of shape) a basket; basket, caldron, kettle, (seething) pot.
rarely (fully); דָּוִיד; from the same as {{h1730}}; loving; David, the youngest son of Jesse; David.
feminine of {{h1730}}; an aunt; aunt, father's sister, uncle's wife.
from {{h1730}}; loving; Dodo, the name of three Israelites; Dodo.
from {{h1730}} and {{h3050}}; love of Jah; Dodavah, an Israelite; Dodavah.
from {{h1731}}; a boiler or basket; also the mandrake (as an aphrodisiac); basket, mandrake.
formed like {{h1736}}; amatory; Dodai, an Israelite; Dodai.
a primitive root; to be sick (as if in menstruation); infirmity.
from {{h1738}}; sick (especially in menstruation); faint, menstruous cloth, she that is sick, having sickness.
from an unused root meaning to be dumb (compare {{h1820}}); silence; figuratively, death; silence.
of uncertain derivation; the hoopoe or else the grouse; lapwing.
from {{h1820}}; stillness; adverbially, silently; abstractly quiet, trust; silence, silent, waiteth.
the same as {{h1745}}; Dumah, a tribe and region of Arabia; Dumah.
from {{h1739}}; sickness; figuratively, loathing; languishing, sorrowful.
a primitive root; to thrust away; figuratively, to cleanse; cast out, purge, wash.
a primitive root; to bruise in a mortar; beat.
from {{h1739}}; sick; figuratively, troubled; faint.
of uncertain derivation; wax; wax.
from {{h1826}}; still; adverbially, silently; dumb, silent, quietly wait.
or (by permutation) דֹּאר; (Joshua 17:11; 1 Kings 4:11), from {{h1755}}; dwelling; Dor, a place in Palestine; Dor.
(Aramaic) probably from {{h1753}}; circle or dwelling; Dura, a place in Babylonia; Dura.
from {{h1752}}; a circle, ball or pile; ball, turn, round about.
or (shortened) דֹּר; from {{h1752}}; properly, a revolution of time, i.e. an age or generation; also a dwelling; age, × evermore, generation, (n-) ever, posterity.
a primitive root; properly, to gyrate (or move in a circle), i.e. to remain; dwell.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1752}}; to reside; dwell.
a primitive root; to leap; be turned.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1854}}; to crumble; be broken to pieces.
or דּוֹשׁ; or דִּישׁ; a primitive root; to trample or thresh; break, tear, thresh, tread out (down), at grass (Jeremiah 50:11, by mistake for {{h1877}}).
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1758}}; to trample; tread down.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h2119}}; to slink, i.e. (by implication) to fear, or (causatively) be formidable; make afraid, dreadful, fear, terrible.
from {{h1760}}; a push, i.e. (by implication) a fall; falling.
(Aramaic) from the equivalent of {{h1760}}; probably a musical instrument (as being struck); instrument of music.
or דָּחַח; (Jeremiah 23:12), a primitive root; to push down; chase, drive away (on), overthrow, outcast, × sore, thrust, totter.

of uncertain derivation; enough (as noun or adverb), used chiefly with preposition in phrases; able, according to, after (ability), among, as (oft as), (more than) enough, from, in, since, (much as is) sufficient(-ly), too much, very, when.
a primitive root; to press, i.e. oppress; thrust, vex.
a primitive root; to urge, i.e. hasten; (be) haste(-ned), pressed on.
of uncertain derivation; millet; millet.
or (shortened) דִּיבֹן; from {{h1727}}; pining:—; Dibon, the name of three places in Palestine; Dibon. (Also, with {{h1410}} added, Dibon-gad.)

(Aramaic) apparently for {{h1668}}; that, used as relative conjunction, and especially (with a preposition) in adverbial phrases; also as preposition of; × as, but, for(-asmuch  ),   now, of, seeing, than, that, therefore, until,   what (-soever), when, which, whom, whose.
from {{h1809}}; properly, dangling, i.e. (by implication) weak or thin; lean, needy, poor (man), weaker.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1777}}; to judge; judge.
or (Job 19:29) דּוּן; from {{h1777}}; judgement (the suit, justice, sentence or tribunal); by implication also strife; cause, judgement, plea, strife.
as if from {{h1768}} and {{h2091}}; of gold; Dizahab, a place in the Desert; Dizahab.
perhaps for {{h1769}}; Dimon, a place in Palestine; Dimon.
feminine of {{h1775}}; Dimonah, a place in Palestine; Dimonah.

or (Genesis 6:3) דּוּן; a primitive root; to rule; by implication to judge (as umpire); also to strive (as at law); contend contend execute (judgment) judge minister judgment plead (the cause) at strife strive.
denominative from {{h1709}}; to fish; fish.
from {{h1770}}; a fisherman; fisher.
intensive from {{h1675}}; a falcon (from its rapid flight); vulture.
of uncertain derivation; ink; ink.
from {{h1777}}; a judge or advocate; judge.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1779}}; judgement.
feminine of {{h1779}}; justice; Dinah, the daughter of Jacob; Dinah.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1781}}; judge.
from a root corresp. to {{h1751}}; a battering-tower; fort.
(Aramaic) partial from uncertain primitive; a Dinaite or inhabitant of some unknown Assyria province; Dinaite.
Diyshon, the same as {{h1788}}; Dishon, the name of two Edomites; Dishon.
from {{h1758}}; threshing-time; threshing.
another form of {{h1787}}; Dishan, an Edomite; Dishan, Dishon.
from {{h1758}}; the leaper, i.e. an antelope; pygarg.

or (fully) דָּאג; (Nehemiah 13:16), from {{h1711}}; a fish (as prolific); or perhaps rather from {{h1672}} (as timid); but still better from {{h1672}} (in the sense of squirming, i.e. moving by the vibratory action of the tail); a fish (often used collectively); fish.
the same as {{h1707}}; Dabbesheth, a place in Palestine; Dabbesheth.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h1700}}; intent, sake.
intensive from {{h1696}}; a word; word.
feminine active participle of {{h1696}} in the sense of driving (compare {{h1699}}); a raft; float.
from {{h1697}} (perhaps in the sense of {{h1699}}); Daberath, a place in Palestine; Dabareh, Daberath.
from {{h1697}}; wordy; Dibri, an Israelite; Dibri.
intensive from the same as {{h1706}}; a sticky mass, i.e. the hump of a camel; hunch (of a camel).
from an unused root meaning to be gummy; honey (from its stickiness); by analogy, syrup; honey(-comb).
a primitive root (compare {{h1794}}); to crumble; transitively, to bruise (literally or figuratively); beat to pieces, break (in pieces), bruise, contrite, crush, destroy, humble, oppress, smite.
from {{h1792}}; crushed (literally powder, or figuratively, contrite); contrite, destruction.
from an unused root (compare {{h1794}}); crushed, i.e. (figuratively) injured; afflicted, oppressed.
(Aramaic) or דָּךְ; (Aramaic), prolonged from {{h1668}}; this; the same, this.
from {{h1794}}; a dashing of surf; wave.
(Aramaic) prolonged from {{h1791}}; this; same, that, this.
a primitive root (compare {{h1790}}, {{h1792}}); to collapse (phys. or mentally); break (sore), contrite, crouch.
from {{h1794}} like {{h1793}}; mutilated; wounded.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h2145}}; properly, a male, i.e. of sheep; ram.
(Aramaic) or דׇּכְרָן (Aramaic); corresponding to {{h2146}}; a register; record.
a doubtful root; to walk gently; go (softly, with).
or (prolonged) דְּדָנֶה; (Ezekiel 25:13), of uncertain derivation; Dedan, the name of two Cushites and of their territory; Dedan.
from {{h1709}}; the fish-god; Dagon, a Philistine deity; Dagon.
a primitive root; to flaunt, i.e. raise a flag; figuratively, to be conspicuous; (set up, with) banners, chiefest.
feminine of {{h1709}}, and meaning the same; fish.
a primitive root; to move rapidly; used only as a denominative from {{h1709}}; to spawn, i.e. become numerous; grow.
a primitive root,; to brood over eggs or young; gather, sit.
apparently from the same as {{h1730}}; the breast (as the seat of love, or from its shape); breast, teat.
from {{h1713}}; a flag; banner, standard.
from {{h1711}}; properly, increase, i.e. grain; corn (floor), wheat.
a primitive root; to mope, i.e. (figuratively) pine; sorrow.
by reduplication from {{h1725}}; a gallop; pransing.
a primitive root; to curvet or move irregularly; pause.
a primitive root (compare {{h1740}}); to be dumb, i.e. (figuratively) dumbfounded; astonished.
(Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; Dahava, a people colonized in Samaria; Dehavites.
(Aramaic) corresponding to {{h2091}}; gold; gold(-en).
or (by orthographical error) רֹדָנִים (1 Chronicles 1:7); a plural of uncertain derivation; Dodanites, or descendants of a son of Javan; Dodanim.
plural of {{h1719}} (as patrial); Dedanites, the descendants or inhabitants of Dedan; Dedanim.
feminine from the same as {{h1728}}; properly, fishery, i.e. a hook for fishing; fish (hook).
an orthographical variation of {{h1709}} as a denominative ({{h1771}}); a fisherman; fisher.
